\par\pard\plain \tx0\li346\fi14\sb60\sl264\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs22\b1\i0\cf7 - Evan:}{\f3\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 <$Scr_Cs::5> Evan is feeling great. He has decided to set his doubts aside and embrace his new relationship with Maggie. However, their year together has not officially started. First, he wanted to make sure that Liz approved of Maggie. Which he already knew she would. Then he wanted to feel the date out a little bit and make sure that Maggie was ready to officially be his girlfriend.<!$Scr_Cs::5>}
\par\plain {\f4\fs22\b1\i0\cf7 - Maggie:}{\f3\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 <$Scr_Cs::5> Although Maggie's feet are hurting, she is charmed by the indoor picnic that Evan surprised her with. She's incredibly impressed that he actually made most of the meal himself. And she is touched that he went out of his way to make sure the meal, and the whole date didn't cost too much. To her, that proved that unlike most of the men she's been with, Evan listens and cares about her needs and wants.<!$Scr_Cs::5><!$Scr_Ps::3>}
\par\pard\plain \tx0\sl168\slmult1\ltrch\loch \f4\fs22\b1\i0\cf7
\par\pard\plain \tx0\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs22\b1\i0\cf5 <$Scr_Ps::2>POV:}{\f3\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 <$Scr_Cs::5> Third person limited, deep (focusing on Evan). }{\f4\fs22\b1\i0\cf1 Important note: }{\f3\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 For this scene, we are going to relax my typical "one scene, one POV" rule. I think in this scene, we can have Evan and Maggie equally sharing the POV. If this turns out well, I may relax these rules more often. When you craft the scene, I want a rich scene, where the readers experience various parts of the scenes from both Maggie and Evan's perspectives.<!$Scr_Cs::5><!$Scr_Ps::2><$Scr_Ps::3>}
